<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>CALIPER DISC BRAKES - SERVICE PROCEDURES - PADS AND CALIPER INSTALLATION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl0401611" svcproctype="install" graphiccount="3">
        <title>PADS AND CALIPER INSTALLATION</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Position inboard pad assembly onto the anchor plate pad lining facing the rotor surface.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Be sure caliper pistons are fully seated in the caliper bores.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Position outboard pad onto caliper and press pad into position. If pad is difficult to
                install, tap pad assembly lightly with a hammer. On 2.88 inch bore calipers, pay attention to the pads
                as there is a left hand side and a right hand side. Pads are marked.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply a liberal but not excessive amount of lubricant to the machined sliding surfaces of
                the caliper, anchor plate, support spring and key. Use Southwest grease NLGI 1-1/2.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If a new caliper is being used, be sure that the bleeder screw is installed (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0401621">Figure 21</hotlnk>and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0401622">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0401621" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401621" filename="../figg04/g0401621.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Exploded View of Single Piston Caliper Assembly (Code 04145)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. OUTBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. INBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. CALIPER SUPPORT KEY</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. SUPPORT KEY RETAINING BOLT</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. CALIPER SUPPORT SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. CALIPER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. PISTON</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. DUST BOOT</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. PISTON SEAL</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. BLEED SCREW</callout1>
                    <callout1>11. ANCHOR PLATE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0401622" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401622" filename="../figg04/g0401622.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Disc Brake Components With Shim Kit</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. CALIPER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. V-WAY SURFACE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SHIM</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. SUPPORT SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. RETAINING BOLT</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. SUPPORT KEY</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. ANCHOR PLATE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Position caliper assembly onto rotor and anchor plate. Be sure caliper and pads are seated
                properly.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Hold caliper in position with machined surfaces of the caliper against the machined surface
                of the anchor plate. The rear caliper will have to be rotated upward to allow the support spring and key
                to be installed. Then position the (caliper shim kit if required) caliper support spring and (oversized
                key kit if required) support key as an assembly between the caliper and anchor plate. Using a hammer,
                lightly tap the support spring and key into position (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401621">Figure 21</hotlnk>,
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401622">Figure 22</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401623">Figure 23</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0401623" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401623" filename="../figg04/g0401623.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Exploded View of Two Piston Caliper Assembly (Codes 04144, 04146, 04237, 04238)
                </caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. OUTBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. INBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SHIELD</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. DUST BOOT</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. PISTON</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. SEAL</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. CALIPER HOUSING</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. TUBE SEAT INSERT</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. BLEEDER SCREW</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. ANCHOR PLATE (BRACKET)</callout1>
                    <callout1>11. SUPPORT SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>12. SUPPORT KEY</callout1>
                    <callout1>13. SUPPORT KEY RETAINING BOLT</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install support key retaining bolt. Tighten bolt to 12-18 lb-ft. (16-24 N&#8226;m).</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Connect brake hose if caliper assembly was removed and bleed brakes. Refer to GROUP 04 -
                BRAKES, HYDRAULIC in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check brake master cylinder fluid. Fill reservoir if necessary.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove vehicle from support stands.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check brakes for proper operation before putting vehicle back in service.</para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
